          <avActivityHighlights>Wind slabs represent the main danger.</avActivityHighlights>
          <avActivityComment>The wind slabs of the last few days are lying on the unfavourable surface of an old snowpack in particular on steep shady slopes. &lt;br/&gt; As a consequence of the southeasterly wind they have increased in size moderately on Wednesday. &lt;br/&gt; Especially adjacent to ridgelines and in gullies and bowls extremely steep terrain: The wind slabs can be released by a single winter sport participant in some cases. &lt;br/&gt; The backcountry touring conditions are generally favourable. Wind slabs require caution.</avActivityComment>
          <snowpackStructureComment>On Sunday, at an altitude of around 1,500 metres, 50 to 100 cm of snow fell widely across the eastern and south-eastern parts of the region, and 30 to 40 cm of snow fell across the rest of the area. The weather conditions facilitated a settling of the snowpack. &lt;br/&gt; The surface of the snowpack will freeze to form a strong crust. Sunshine and high temperatures will give rise from the middle of the day to gradual softening of the snowpack on steep sunny slopes at low and intermediate altitudes. &lt;br/&gt; Especially adjacent to ridgelines in all aspects: The sometimes strong wind has transported the new snow. Here snow depths vary greatly, depending on the infuence of the wind. &lt;br/&gt; Weak layers exist in the snowpack in particular on steep shady slopes.</snowpackStructureComment>
          <tendencyComment>The weather conditions will facilitate a gradual strengthening of the near-surface layers in particular on sunny slopes. The various wind slabs have bonded with the old snowpack.</tendencyComment>
